76561198102399227,Recommended,255390,18394908,"Posted: 9 October, 2015",all,Wujek Spenser,"I'm suprised Max: The Curse of Brotherhood is not widely mentioned, as it is fun little game.It's supposed to be a sequel to Max and the Magic Marker, which I didn't play. But it is not a big loss. Out of couriosity I checked the other game on YouTube and my conclusion is, that developers where toying with the idea before delivering the real deal which is Curse of Brotherhood. And I'm suprised it didn't get the hype and reach as wide as Ori and the Blind Forest, as both are released by Microsoft studios.The kid named Max, who got rid of his brother via magic spell that he found on the internet. His brother Felix is captured through portal into another wolrd and Max jumps right after him realizing the consequences of his action. From now on you control Max, who get to use a magic marker. A simple item that let's you solve the puzzles throughout the game mixed with platforming. The marker allows you draw rock pillars, branches, lianes, water geysers at certain spots leaving you to figure out how to do it to proceed further or solve the puzzles. Not all of it will be available from the beginning, but as it is straight-forward side-scroller, there won't be any backtracking.Now, I need to mention that I play with my X360 controller and I have no idea how the game works with keyboard control. As for the gamepad it felt very smooth, both for controling Max and drawing stuff with the marker. Smooth and nice graphic won't obscure anything and light tutorial won't leave you clueless as to how to interact with objects. You will be able to draw Os from branches, cut them by the base and use it as an object you can climb onto. Some enemies apart from hazzards also serve as a solution to the puzzle. You also have to combine marker's abilities. All of that is explained in the game so you know how, but thankfully doesn't serve as a guide. The difficulty of the puzzles is various however. Normaly you'll be able to go through with very brief moments of reflection. Sometimes you may be stuck for longer, but never long enough to make you frustrated. Colorful and childish theme of the game may suggest it is for younger players and I encourage them to try it.There are collectibles in the game, but they serve no other purpose, than to chill your eventual OCD. There are evil eyes to collect and these may be placed in the areas that will take you longer to figure acces to. There are also pieces of the amulet of the Old Lady (she's kinda guiding you through the magic land), much harder to get. The main problem with it, is that the camera is very stiff and concetrated on Max. Sometimes you may be able to spot evil eye somewhere on the corner of the screen, but getting some of them requies leap of faith.The artstyle is simple but gorgeous, there is also superb voice-acting, a bit unexpected from a small game. Normally I play on my PC connected to 32"" LED TV so I can enjoy the graphics of such colorful games. However, considering the overall quality of the graphics it shouldn't struggle on older gear, but it does. I own 8GB RAM Laptop with 1GB RAM graphics card and quad core processor and had huge problem with cutscenes. I got the sound without visuals or got it with miserable framerate. No struggles on a PC, though.As Max: The Curse of Brotherhood is puzzle-platformer, have in mind it will play different than a straight-forward platformer. It is not very demanding game, there's a free demo available on Steam, that I would reccomend to try out first before buying the full game. It was fun for me.7/10"
76561197972144762,Recommended,255390,12036671,"Posted: 9 September, 2014",all,Sathlin,I am loving this game.  Great artwork.  Great platforming.  Very uniquie Mechanic as well.Buy it.
,Recommended,255390,26193034,"Posted: 23 October, 2016",all,"""Bob"" the Space Cadet","Max: The Curse of the Brotherhood is a pretty slick puzzle platformer. It's well animated with good cut scenes, the graphics look good, and it's very nicely voiced too. The first Max and the Magic Marker game was pretty good, but this is a vast improvement. Instead of drawing items while making sure you have enough ink to do so, all marker actions are context specific and ink management is no longer a concern, which makes the puzzles a lot tighter with a specific solution, but also more enjoyable because you'll always have the right amount of ink to find the correct solution to each puzzle/obstacle.You don't need to play the first game at all to enjoy the Curse of the Brotherhood, so feel free to skip the first game entirely. The plot of this game doesn't tie in with the first much at all, and closely resembles the 1986 David Bowie film ""Labyrinth"", in which an older sibling asks the goblin king (in the case of Max, he goes on the internet and asks an old man with a mustache... creepy) to take his/her younger brother away, and when it actually works he/she has to go into a fantasy land to save him.I played Max on a laptop and tried a number of input methods, the best by far I found to be using an Xinput compatible controller (I used an FC30 Pro, but any Xbox style controller should do the job). Touch screen wasn't usable which was pretty disappointing, and though the mouse trackpad did work, some time-sensitive actions were impossible to carry out using the trackpad. A regular mouse would probably be fine, but the controller has the advantage of the magic marker snapping-to on the nearest interactive object, and continuous direction by holding down the analogue stick, which is important in the later levels where you have to raise yourself up on high platforms quite quickly.8/10 - Worthmarkingin your wishlist if you like puzzle platformers"
