76561198086457357,Recommended,255390,18027132,"Posted: 14 September, 2015",all,Jelogisa,"A very pretty game, with a colorful and enticing universe. It's a platformer with a good atmosphere and some imagination. It's rather on the 'casual' side: it's very varied and not too difficult, which will make you feel like you're good at this game.Graphics: Great. Sometimes you feel like you're into an animation movie.Physics: Great. All objects behave, move and fall like you'd expect: boulders, vines, branches, roots, water and jets, ...Game mechanics: Good. You change objects from the scenery with your magical pen to reach your objectives (progress through a level, block enemies, succeed in an impossible jump, ...) You can only do so starting at a few select spots in every level.Gameplay: Good. It's dynamic, the setting changes often, so you'll have to find new ways to deal with the new challenges, and it's never feels repetitive or boring.Story/Dialogue/Voice acting: Good (nothing to write home about, but good)Level design: good to great (some good ideas, lots of imagination in some areas).Difficulty: never too difficult (At most you'll retry a couple of times before overcoming an obstacle, when you die you lose less than a minute of progression).Length: Short (about 7 hours to reach the end, a bit more to find all secrets in all levels). The progression is rather fast, so you'd have traveled a long way at the end of the game.All in all, a good game that kept me wanting for more to the very end."
,Recommended,255390,18048556,"Posted: 15 September, 2015",all,TheDContinuum,"This is a fun little game! You play as Max, who is trying to find his brother, wielding a magic marker with the power to create and manipulate objects in this puzzle-platformer. It's a mix of untimed puzzles, plus ones you have to do (sometimes literally) on the fly. Some of the puzzles require split-second timing where you're being chased, but parts that are super time-sensitive go into a slow-motion for a few seconds to allow you to quickly analyze the situation and act appropriately. They are (usually) very generous with checkpoints, so even if you're not so good at the platforming aspects (like me), you won't have far to go when you have to repeat a level. The magic marker mechanic is really well done, with you being able to adjust the height of pillars for jumping on, create different shapes out of branches for either jumping on or chopping down and using for other purposes, vines for swinging and climbing, water jets where you get to decide their path, and goodness, gracious great balls of fire for blowing up enemies and barriers.Pros:+ Good Music+ Good voice acting (I seriously felt bad for Max when he jumps into lava and screams in genuine agony)+ Good art (it has characters with a Jimmy Neutron feel but with great backgrounds)+ Novel mechanic (drawing/manipulating objects)+ Collectibles for added challenge+ Puzzles took thought but were not brain-breakingNeutral:~ Decent length, though I would have liked more. I got 11 hours out of it, including my bad platforming skills and a lot of redos, and finding all the collectibles. So, not super short, but I would have loved more.Cons:- The marker is not always at the ready, making it feel sluggish sometimes as you have to wait for it to appear for use. This doesn't affect the actual game play, since it's created with the sluggishness in mind, but it's a tad annoying at times. Likewise, the effect of your marker (e.g. lifting up a platform) doesn't always keep up with how fast you make it, with a similarly sluggish feel. Not a deal-breaker, since I still played the game to completion, including collectibles, but it was annoying.- This is not a con for me, but maybe for others: The puzzles aren't maddeningly difficult, as some people may prefer. A lot of the difficulty comes from the split-second timing, but the untimed puzzles take at most a few minutes to puzzle out.Overall: 9/10. Would replay."
